## Supabase — connect in Cursor (preferred; no terminal)

Use **Supabase MCP** so login happens in Cursor’s UI, not `npx supabase login`.

1. **Cursor Settings** → **Tools & MCP**
2. Find **supabase** (from `.cursor/mcp.json` in this project)
3. Click **Connect** (or click **Needs authentication** under the server name if Connect fails)
4. Browser opens → log in to Supabase → **Authorize Cursor**
5. Redirect should go to `cursor://…` (handled by Cursor). **Not** `http://127.0.0.1:…` — that URL is only for the CLI and will not save auth in Cursor.
6. Green status + tools enabled = connected. Agent can run migrations via MCP `apply_migration` / `list_migrations`.

If OAuth hangs: **View → Output → MCP: supabase**, copy the `https://api.supabase.com/v1/oauth/authorize?...` URL, open it in your normal browser, complete auth.

Optional: scope to one project in `.cursor/mcp.json`:
`"url": "https://mcp.supabase.com/mcp?project_ref=YOUR_REF"`

## Supabase — browser paste popup (no terminal; user cannot use shell)

When the user cannot use the terminal or OAuth fails:

1. Run `npm run dev` in the frontend repo (port **5174**)
2. Open **http://localhost:5174/cursor-paste** (browser MCP or tell user the URL)
3. User pastes Supabase PAT + project ref → clicks **Save for Cursor**
4. When user says **credentials saved**, read `.cursor/local/deploy.env` first — do not ask again

If MCP OAuth failed but `deploy.env` has a PAT, patch `.cursor/mcp.json`:

```json
"supabase": {
  "type": "http",
  "url": "https://mcp.supabase.com/mcp?project_ref=YOUR_REF",
  "headers": { "Authorization": "Bearer ${env:SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN}" }
}
```

Set Windows user env `SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN` from deploy.env if `${env:...}` interpolation is needed. User reloads MCP in Cursor Settings → Tools & MCP.

Verify save: `GET http://localhost:5174/api/agent/credentials/status` (masked values only).

## Supabase CLI fallback (terminal only)

CLI auth is **not** in Credential Manager. After login, token lives at:

`C:\Users\dolab\.supabase\access-token`

For agents without MCP, check (gitignored):

`.cursor/local/deploy.env`

Required variables in `deploy.env`:

```
SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN=sbp_...
SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF=xxxxxxxx
```

Get token: Supabase Dashboard → Account → Access Tokens, or run `npx supabase login` in an **interactive** terminal (keep it open until browser redirects to `http://127.0.0.1:PORT/?code=...`).

**OAuth popup alone is not enough** — the Supabase CLI must be running and listening on that localhost port when the browser returns.

## Supabase push workflow

From backend repo:

```powershell
cd "c:\Users\dolab\Downloads\tradepro-backend"
# Load token if deploy.env exists
if (Test-Path "..\\Bathroom Sales Estimation Platform\\.cursor\\local\\deploy.env") {
  Get-Content "..\\Bathroom Sales Estimation Platform\\.cursor\\local\\deploy.env" | ForEach-Object {
    if ($_ -match '^([^#=]+)=(.*)$') { Set-Item -Path "env:$($matches[1].Trim())" -Value $matches[2].Trim() }
  }
}
npx supabase link --project-ref $env:SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF
npm run supabase:push
```

Backend migrations: `tradepro-backend/supabase/migrations/`
Local config name: `project_id = "tradepro"` in `supabase/config.toml` (link uses cloud project ref, not this string).

## What not to do

- Do not scan `%USERPROFILE%`, Downloads, or agent transcripts for repo URLs or tokens
- Do not commit `.cursor/local/deploy.env`, `.env.local`, or access tokens
- Do not create new GitHub repos unless the user asks — use the two remotes above
